&lt;/ul&gt;</description></item><item><title>[Solution] C++ std::overflow_error — Arithmetic Overflow Fix</title><link>https://errorcode.excellentwiki.com/languages/cpp/overflowerror/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://errorcode.excellentwiki.com/languages/cpp/overflowerror/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="solution-c-stdoverflow_error--arithmetic-overflow-fix"&gt;[Solution] C++ std::overflow_error — Arithmetic Overflow Fix&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A &lt;code&gt;std::overflow_error&lt;/code&gt; is thrown when an arithmetic operation produces a result that exceeds the maximum representable value for the given type. This applies to both integers (where overflow is undefined behavior for signed types) and floating-point (where it produces infinity). Unlike unsigned integer overflow (which wraps around), signed integer overflow is undefined behavior in C++.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="why-stdoverflow_error-occurs"&gt;Why std::overflow_error Occurs&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Common causes include adding or multiplying large integers, computing factorials of large numbers, accumulating values without checking bounds, and multiplying floating-point values that produce infinity.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>